10
00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:42.720
We did. Eating at the table was an important ritual. It was something we did every day.

11
00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:46.720
And quite often, it was the only time we could get together and chat.

12
00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:52.720
I think there's something very comforting about eating good food and being with the people your closest to.

13
00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.720
And now, I do the same with my own family.

14
00:00:55.720 --> 00:01:02.720
The kids are more likely to open up. Talk more easily about their day or something troubling them while they're eating.

15
00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:07.720
Well, the dinner table is a space that families across the world get together at.

16
00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:09.720
To not only eat, but chat.

17
00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:15.720
And is often the only point in the day or week that the whole family gather together.

18
00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:20.720
In this program, we'll be discussing how people behave at the table.

19
00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:24.720
And of course, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

20
00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:34.720
But first, I have a question for you, Beth. In 2016, a couple from Germany, won the world record for the fastest time to set a dinner table.

21
00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:37.720
But how long did it take them? Was it a?

22
00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:44.720
25 seconds? B? One minute and five seconds? Or C? Two minutes and five seconds?

23
00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:49.720
Surely not 25 seconds. I will guess. One minute, five seconds.

24
00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.720
Okay, Beth, I'll reveal the answer later in the program.

25
00:01:52.720 --> 00:02:00.720
Now, while eating with a group, you might feel that you need to act in a certain way because of the people around you.

26
00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:06.720
Philip Apperi, a psychotherapist and author, thinks we should try to be ourselves as much as possible.

27
00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:10.720
As she told BBC World Service Program, the food chain.

28
00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:15.720
In any group, we find a role.

29
00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:23.720
And if we're only in one group, if we're only ever with our family, we might think, oh, I'm the funny one. He's the wise one.

30
00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:27.720
We might think that's who we are. And then we go to another group.

31
00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:38.720
And then we find, oh, I'm the wise one. And I think if you feel like you're assigned a role in your family, I just think take that with a little bit of a pinch of salt.

32
00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:47.720
When you spend time with the same group of people, you might start to think of yourself as the funny one or the wise one.

33
00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:56.720
When we say the one, we describe a person by using a particular and prominent characteristic they have.

34
00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:59.720
If you're very tall, you might be the tall one.

35
00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:04.720
However, Philip says we should take these labels with a pinch of salt.

36
00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:10.720
An idiom meaning you shouldn't believe or do everything you are told or that's expected of you.

37
00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:15.720
Now over time, interactions at the dinner table have changed.

38
00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:23.720
In the past, children were sometimes seated on a different table to adults or tolls they should be seen and not heard.

39
00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:30.720
An old fashioned phrase emphasizing that children should be quiet and always on their best behavior.

40
00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:46.720
And Brea Medis Fernandez, a writer and founder of Free Black Motherhood spoke about older generations' reactions to children asking awkward questions at the dinner table to BBC World Service program The Food Chain.

41
00:03:46.720 --> 00:04:09.720
So it's a mixed bag. It's overwhelmingly positive, but I also know that it is kind of a bit of a culture shock for them to hear my children ask the questions that they asked because our children haven't really been raised with that line of demarcation between the adult table and the key at table.

42
00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:18.720
Amberia says that the older generations' reactions to her children's questions at the table can be a mixed bag.

43
00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:27.720
A mixed bag is a situation that can have positive and negative aspects. She also says that it's a culture shock for them.

44
00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:32.720
A sense of feeling uncertain because you're in a different environment to usual.

45
00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:42.720
I think it's time I revealed the answer to my question. I asked you what the world record is for the fastest time to set a dinner table.

46
00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:45.720
And I said it was one minute and five seconds.

47
00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.720
And that was the right answer. That's not very long is it.

48
00:04:49.720 --> 00:05:01.720
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned from this program starting with OpenUp. A phrase or verb meaning, speak more easily than usual particularly about worries or problems.

49
00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:08.720
If someone is the funny one or the wise one, they're labeled by that particular characteristic.

50
00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:13.720
To take something with a pinch of salt means you shouldn't believe everything you're told.

51
00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:21.720
Children should be seen and not heard is an old fashioned phrase that means children should be quiet and behave well.

52
00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:26.720
A mixed bag means something has both positive and negative aspects.

53
00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:35.720
Finally, a culture shock is an uncertain feeling because you're in a new environment. Once again, our six minutes are up.

